The second wave of COVID-19 in Nigeria is spreading faster than expected as 1,664 new confirmed cases from across the were reported on Wednesday night, taking the country’s total to 94,369, according to the latest update by the Nigeria Centre for Disease Control (NCDC). Earlier today,  the Lagos University Teaching Hospital (LUTH), raised an alarm, warning Nigerians to head COVID-19 protocols as the second wave of the disease has shown that it can and does spread faster while Nigerians continue to handle their safety with apparent levity. In a statement by the Chief Medical Director of LUTH, Professor Chris Bode, said: “The resurgence of COVID-19, through the newly mutated form, is ravaging our land, claiming many lives. ABUJA DOCTOR REVEALS HOW MOST NIGERIA MEN ARE NOW OVERCOMING TERRIBLE BEDROOM PERFORMANCE DUE TO THIS BRILLIANT DISCOVERY. DON'T BE A VICTIM! “Unlike what we witnessed in the first wave, this one is even more easily transmitted and deadlier too. “It is, therefore, imperative for everyone, first and foremost, accept that COVID-19 pandemic is not over, and we must prepare to confront it all over again. Foundation Wants More Support For Widows Democrats Poised To Control US Senate, Giving Biden Upper Hand “What we see on the streets, worship centres and social interactions, parties and daily activities call for concern. “In a period when the ‘enemy’ has doubled back and is attacking us ferociously, we seem to be celebrating a false victory and denying the danger is still around us. “We need to observe all the basic rules we have been following all along and wake up to the present reality.’’ The latest NCDC update gathered from 22 states and the Federal Capital Territory (FCT), and made public via the Agency’s verified Twitter handle, @NCDCgov, Lagos recorded 642 new cases, FCT- 407, Plateau – 160, Kaduna – 83 and Rivers – 62, to make up the top five states with highest cases for Wednesday. The update also showed that 903 persons were discharged after they recovered from the virus, taking the total number of recoveries to 77,299 from across the country. The NCDC also disclosed that a total of 756 of these recoveries were achieved through its community recoveries with 388 in Lagos, 261 in Kaduna, 87 in Plateau and 20 in Imo states. The NCDC tweeted: “Our discharges today include 388 community recoveries in Lagos State, 261 in Kaduna State, 87 in Plateau State and 20 in Imo State managed in line with guidelines.” Our discharges today include 388 community recoveries in Lagos State, 261 in Kaduna State, 87 in Plateau State and 20 in Imo State managed in line with guidelines.A breakdown of cases by state can be found via https://t.co/zQrpNeOfet pic.twitter.com/OHWAzE1Lhc The NCDC also revealed that there were also five deaths recorded on Wednesday, taking Nigeria’s COVID-19 death toll to 1,324. Breakdown of the Lagos-642 FCT-407 Plateau-160 Kaduna-83 Rivers-62 Adamawa-47 Nasarawa-38 Abia-29 Edo-28 Anambra-27 Niger-24 Ogun-24 Imo-15 Oyo-14 Kano-12 Osun-12 Borno-9 Delta-7 Enugu-7 Bauchi-5 Ekiti-5 Sokoto-5 Jigawa-2  1664 new cases of #COVID19Nigeria;Lagos-642FCT-407Plateau-160Kaduna-83Rivers-62Adamawa-47Nasarawa-38Abia-29Edo-28Anambra-27Niger-24Ogun-24Imo-15Oyo-14Kano-12Osun-12Borno-9Delta-7Enugu-7Bauchi-5Ekiti-5Sokoto-5Jigawa-2 pic.twitter.com/T5AWc29Hb7